\begin_layout Section
Designing Objects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We seperate the information into two domain objects: Intravenous and Bag.
 The intravenous represents a real world intravenous using a bag to inject
 it to a patient's body, therefore the intravenous contains a bag object
 reference.
 The information is seperated, so that the bag has access to the drug, volume
 and concentration it contains, and the intravenous has access to its fields
 dose, rate , duration and its bag's drug and volume (all the fields except
 the concentration).
 The intravenous access' restrictions are applied by extracting a bag interface
 containing only the drug and volume.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first use-case (from 2.1) is described according to the new design (figure
 3.3).
 A clinician sets values to the intravenous' dose and duration, in response,
 the intravenous calculates the bag's drug's value.
 Then a clinician set value to the bag's volume, in response the bag calculates
 its concentration's value.
 Additionaly, the bag calls to the intravenous 
\emph on
indirectly
\emph default
 to calculate its rate's value according to the bag's volume's new value.
\end_layout

